Review: Was fairly impressed at the beginning. The black and white romance with Bernstein’s music layered throughout, creating an almost storybook romance reflecting the musicals he wrote for and emulating the style of old black and white pictures: really cool. The transition to color as we start facing the reality of the man who wrote that music: also cool. But after that? Way too shallow. I wasn’t really left with much, the writing felt overly embellished without any real substance, and…

I liked that they really committed to the anime bit, with the music and changing animation styles super engaging. So glad it was not just an adaptation, excellent storytelling and real character development, becoming simultaneously an homage and critique of the original. Tbh I wasn’t the biggest fan of the voice acting at times. Some were better than others but as a whole felt a little off. Just some of the tonal elements of the voice acting. But overall really solid show.
Really every scene or song with Reneé Rapp is just on a whole other level than every other one. A chilling performer, incredible. Rest of the movie was fun.

Very charming and sincere. Real skill from the director to do that, it wouldn’t take much to make this very cringe. But I still think Chalamet was not the right choice here (and I love Chalamet usually!), his face just too broody and serious for the role and I’m not a big fan of his singing voice but oh well, lucky enough the movie had good bones to make me not think about it that much.

Very solid adaptation. Great songs and great performers, though I wasn’t a big fan of the dancing/staging. Lacks some of the emotional depth of a live performance, and lacked significant thematic depth compared to the book (so many of the characters just not adequately explored), but still very enjoyable.

Such interesting character development. Something that particularly stuck out for me was the setting here. The suburbs just feel so sinister, and it wraps the entire movie in it. Just made me feel doubly unsettled, especially alongside the score.

When you grow your children as extensions of yourself, your insecurities, your failures, your dreams, and your own fucked up values, the legacy you are bestowing upon them is misery and death. A heartbreaking film with an ensemble cast that worked together spectacularly, using the world of wrestling as an excellent vessel, even though I don’t care at all about it. Really cool exploration of emotion through the camera-work and blocking, and I loved the religious themes that threaded maliciously through the film. Zac Efron: amazing.
Too much excrement material on second watch but still funny

Excellent character development over the course of this short series. Yeun and Wong did incredible, their arcs incredibly compelling, and what a finale with the two of them. Amazing ending, last two episodes were marvelous. Screw Netflix and their password sharing rules for keeping them from me for so long.

I liked that the old people who are really into war stuff were really into this in the theater, even though the entire movie was just making fun of it and the people who wage it. The movie was engaging and I really liked Joaquin Phoenix, but nothing really distinctive about it, feels like a movie I’ve seen a bunch of times before.

Epic. Haven’t seen any of the older Japanese Godzilla movies, but this one certainly puts the atrocious American ones to complete shame. Emotional and gripping storytelling, and while the Godzilla fight sequences were cool and all, the character development and larger war/atomic bomb/WW2 ideas were really well executed. Really cool exploration of guilt and how to move on from a war in which atrocities were committed by and to a population.
Wish the second half had as much funny and singing (none) as the first half
